SIMPLE: pet
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: pet
<hw>pet</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly
<ets>peat</ets>, perhaps from Ir. <ets>peat</ets>, akin to Gael.
<ets>peata</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cade lamb; a lamb brought up
by hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any person especially cherished and indulged; a
fondling; a darling; often, a favorite child; <as>as, a teacher's
<ex>pet</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The love of cronies, <qex>pets</qex>, and favorites.</q>
<rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[Prob. fr. <er>Pet</er> a fondling, hence, the
behavior or humor of a spoiled child.]</ety> <def>A slight fit of
peevishness or fretfulness.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In a <xex>pet</xex> she started
up.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Any animal kept as a companion, usually in or around
one's home, typically domesticated and cared for attentively and often
affectionately. Distinguished from animals raised for food or to perform
useful tasks, as a <contr>draft animal</contr> or a <contr>farm
animal</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>pet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: pet
<hw>pet</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Petted; indulged; favorite; admired;
cherished; <as>as, a <ex>pet</ex> child; a <ex>pet</ex> lamb; a
<ex>pet</ex> theory; a <ex>pet</ex> animal.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some young lady's <qex>pet</qex> curate.</q> <rj><qau>F.
Harrison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pet cock</b></col>. <ety>[Perh. for <ets>petty
cock</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <cd>A little faucet in a water
pipe or pump, to let air out, or at the end of a steam cylinder, to
drain it.</cd> <altsp>[Also spelled
<asp>petcock</asp>.]</altsp></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pet
<hw>Pet</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Petted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Petting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To treat as a pet; to fondle; to
indulge; <as>as, she was <ex>petted</ex> and spoiled</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pet
<hw>Pet</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be a pet.</def>
<rj><au>Feltham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Petal</ent>⟦br⟧
